Abstract

CTSclocks is an R package which includes a number of cell-type specific epigenetic clocks so as to quantify biological age at cell-type resolution. At present, the package can be used to estimate DNAm-Age for neurons and glia in brain, and for hepatocytes in liver. In addition, the package also provides two tissue-specific clocks that allow estimation of DNAm-Age at the tissue level (for brain and liver).

Package

CTSclocks 0.0.1

1 Motivation and Background

The ability to accurately quantify biological age could help monitor and control healthy aging. Epigenetic clocks have emerged as promising tools for estimating biological age, yet so far, most of these clocks have been developed in the context of heterogeneous bulk tissues, which does not inform us about the biological age of individual cell-types. Thus, there is a need to develop epigenetic clocks that are not confounded by cell-type heterogeneity and that can yield biological age estimates at cell-type resolution. Here we present a tutorial on the implementation of cell-type and tissue-specific epigenetic DNA methylation-based clocks for brain and liver, focusing on 3 cell-types: neurons, glia and hepatocytes. In future, we hope to expand this package to include cell-type and tissue-specific clocks for a broader range of cell and tissue-types. Of note, all epigenetic clocks implemented in this package adjust for cell-type heterogeneity in the sense that the CpGs making up the clocks are not just tracking age-related changes in cell-type composition. The difference between the cell-type and tissue-specific clocks is that the cell-type specific ones are trained from CpGs that change with age specifically in the given cell-type (hence this is naturally adjusted for cell-type heterogeneity), whereas the tissue-specific clocks are trained on CpGs that change with age independently of cell-type compositional changes. Hence the latter dont inform about which cell-types a CpG is changing in.

2 Data used in this tutorial

2.1 Bulk PFC data and sorted neuron data

  • The bulk prefrontal cortex (PFC) data is from Murphy et al.This is an Illumina 450k dataset encompassing 38 normal PFC tissue samples and 37 PFC major depressive disorder samples. Only controls are used here. (MurphyGSE88890.rda)
  • The sorted PFC neuron data is from Pai et al.This is an Illumina EPIC dataset encompassing 33 normal neuron tissue samples, 35 schizophrenia samples and 32 bipolar disorder neuron samples. Only controls are used here. (PaiGSE112179.rda)

2.2 A sample data of bulk liver

  • The sample liver data from GSE107038 contains 39 normal liver samples and part of probes. (ExampleData_Liver.Rd)

2.3 Clocks for Brain

  • Neu-In clock (Neu-InCoef.rda)
  • Neu-Sin clock (Neu-SinCoef.rda)
  • Glia-In clock (Glia-InCoef.rda)
  • Glia-Sin clock (Glia-SinCoef.rda)
  • Brain clock (BrainCoef.rda)

2.4 Clocks for Liver

  • Hepatocyte clock (HepClock.rda)
  • Liver clock (LiverClock.rda)



3 Application of Neu/Glia/Brain clocks

3.1 Neu-In, Glia-In and Brain clocks

  • For bulk data, these clocks should be applied on centered and scaled to unit standard deviation residuals obtained after adjustment for cell-type fractions.
  • For sorted data, these clocks should be applied on centered and scaled to unit standard deviation beta matrix.
  • Here we apply Neu-In clock on a bulk PFC data from Murphy et al and a sorted neuron data from Pai et al.The Glia-In and Brain clocks work the same way with Neu-In clock.

3.1.1 Bulk data

library(CTSclocks)

data(MurphyGSE88890)
agePred.v = CTSclockAge(beta.m, CTSclock = 'Neu-In', dataType = 'bulk', CTF.m = NULL, tissue = 'brain')
## [1] "Processing the data may take some time. Don't worry."

3.1.2 Sorted data

library(CTSclocks)

data(PaiGSE112179)
agePred.v = CTSclockAge(beta.m, CTSclock = 'Neu-In', dataType = 'sorted', CTF.m = NULL, tissue = 'brain')



3.2 Neu-Sin and Glia-Sin clocks

  • For both bulk data and sorted data, these clocks should be applied directly on the beta matrix.
  • Here we apply Neu-In clock on a bulk PFC data from Murphy et al and a sorted neuron data from Pai et al.The Glia-Sin clock works the same way with Neu-Sin clock.

3.2.1 Bulk data

library(CTSclocks)

data(MurphyGSE88890)
agePred.v = CTSclockAge(beta.m, CTSclock = 'Neu-Sin', dataType = 'bulk', CTF.m = NULL, tissue = 'brain')

3.2.2 Sorted data

library(CTSclocks)

data(PaiGSE112179)
agePred.v = CTSclockAge(beta.m, CTSclock = 'Neu-Sin', dataType = 'sorted', CTF.m = NULL, tissue = 'brain')



4 Application of Hepatocyte/Liver clocks

For Hep clock

library(CTSclocks)

data(ExampleData_Liver)
agePred.v = CTSclockAge(Test.m, CTSclock = 'Hep', dataType = 'bulk', CTF.m = NULL, tissue = 'otherTissue')

Same steps for the liver clock

library(CTSclocks)

data(ExampleData_Liver)
agePred.v = CTSclockAge(Test.m, CTSclock = 'Liver', dataType = 'bulk', CTF.m = NULL, tissue = 'otherTissue')
